  <a href="#1" id="1">
   Changsha, June 19 (XINHUA) -- This capital of central China's Hunan province has been hit by floods in the wake of a succession of rainstorms on the upper and middle reaches of the Xiangjiang River.
  </a>
  <a href="#2" id="2">
   The water level of the river, which flows through Changsha, is still rising sharply, according to local sources.
  </a>
  <a href="#3" id="3">
   Flood water has entered urban and suburban areas of Wuzhou city, and most of its transport and telecommunications with the outside were suspended.
  </a>
  <a href="#4" id="4">
   Meanwhile, drought is continuing to blight most areas of northern China and northeastern China, with about 15.3 million hectares of land affected.
  </a>
  <a href="#5" id="5">
   Comrade Wen Jiabao [member of CPC Central Committee Secretariat] and his party left Changsha for Zhuzhou and Xiangtan yesterday.
  </a>
  <a href="#6" id="6">
   Fuzhou, June 22 (CNS) -- Flood lasting for ten or more days in Fujian Province has brought about heavy losses in agriculture there.
  </a>
  <a href="#7" id="7">
   After listening to reports submitted by the two cities on their efforts to fight the flooding and do relief work, he issued important instructions.
  </a>
  <a href="#8" id="8">
   Comrade Wen Jiabao fully affirmed the initial victories that the two cities have scored in their flood fighting and relief work under the leadership of the provincial party committee and government.
  </a>
  <a href="#9" id="9">
   Meanwhile, he said, tension has been eased in the Pearl River delta as the latest tropical storm has been weakened after landing in Yangjiang city, Guangdong Province.
  </a>
